# Nonprofit Articles of Incorporation

Produces a compliant, filing-ready nonprofit Articles document optimized for 501(c)(3) recognition.

## Prerequisites

1. State of incorporation and entity type (nonprofit/charitable).
2. Proposed legal name and name availability check status.
3. Registered agent name, physical street address, and consent status.
4. Mission statement, planned activities, beneficiaries, and geographic scope.
5. 501(c)(3) intent and exempt category(ies) (charitable, educational, religious, scientific, etc.).
6. Membership structure decision (members vs no members) and voting rights.
7. Board structure: fixed number or range; initial directors if required by state.
8. Incorporator name(s) and mailing addresses.
9. Effective date (upon filing or delayed date).
10. State-specific required clauses, forms, fees, and attachments.

## Output Structure / Process

**1. State Law Research Checklist**
- Identify controlling nonprofit statute and required article content.
- Confirm naming rules and required designators/restrictions.
- Confirm registered agent requirements and consent form.
- Confirm minimum director count and whether directors/officers must be listed.
- Confirm whether member structure must be stated.
- Confirm indemnification/liability limitation permissibility.
- Confirm filing fee, form, and submission method.
- Flag any state-specific charitable or AG registration triggers.

**2. Data Intake Table**
| Field | Required | Notes |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Corporation name | Yes | Must be distinguishable and compliant with state rules. |
| State of incorporation | Yes | Drives statutory requirements and forms. |
| Registered agent + address | Yes | Physical address in-state; no PO boxes. |
| Purpose/activities | Yes | Must fit 501(c)(3) exempt purposes. |
| Membership structure | Yes | “No members” or member classes/rights. |
| Directors | Varies | Required if state mandates; otherwise optional. |
| Officers | Varies | Required if state mandates; otherwise optional. |
| Incorporators | Yes | Names and addresses. |
| Effective date | Optional | Immediate or delayed (state limits apply). |
| Indemnification/limitation | Optional | Only if permitted by state law. |

**3. Article Outline (Customize Per State)**
| Article | Required | Content |
| --- | --- | --- |
| I. Name | Yes | Exact legal name. |
| II. Registered Agent/Office | Yes | Agent name and physical address. |
| III. Purpose | Yes | 501(c)(3) exempt purpose + specific activities. |
| IV. 501(c)(3) Limits | Yes | Inurement, lobbying, political activity limits. |
| V. Dissolution | Yes | Asset dedication to 501(c)(3)/government. |
| VI. Members | Varies | “No members” or member classes/rights. |
| VII. Directors/Officers | Varies | Number/range, selection if required. |
| VIII. Incorporators | Yes | Names/addresses + signature blocks. |
| IX. Duration/Effective Date | Optional | Perpetual + effective date. |
| X. Optional Protections | Optional | Indemnification/limitation if allowed. |

**4. Core Clause Templates (Edit to State Requirements)**
```text
PURPOSE (501(c)(3)):
This corporation is organized exclusively for charitable, educational, religious, and scientific purposes within the meaning of Section 501(c)(3) of the Internal Revenue Code, as amended, and for no other purpose.

INUREMENT:
No part of the net earnings of the corporation shall inure to the benefit of, or be distributable to, its directors, officers, members, or other private persons, except that the corporation shall be authorized to pay reasonable compensation for services rendered and to make payments in furtherance of its purposes.

LOBBYING / POLITICAL ACTIVITY:
No substantial part of the activities of the corporation shall be the carrying on of propaganda or otherwise attempting to influence legislation, and the corporation shall not participate in or intervene in any political campaign on behalf of or in opposition to any candidate for public office.

DISSOLUTION:
Upon dissolution, assets shall be distributed for one or more exempt purposes within the meaning of Section 501(c)(3) of the Internal Revenue Code, or to the federal government or a state or local government for a public purpose. Any such assets not so disposed of shall be disposed of by a court of competent jurisdiction exclusively for such purposes.
```

**5. Optional Provisions (Only If Allowed)**
- Indemnification to the fullest extent permitted by state law.
- Limitation of director liability consistent with state statute.
- Bylaw authority clause for board/member adoption.
- Amendment clause protecting 501(c)(3) purposes.

**6. Formatting & Filing Package Checklist**
- Article headings labeled and consistent.
- Names/addresses verified; no PO boxes for agent.
- Signature blocks for incorporators; notary blocks if required.
- State cover sheet and agent consent attached if required.
- Filing fee and method confirmed.

**7. Compliance Review Checklist**
- Purpose and dissolution clauses satisfy 501(c)(3) organizational test.
- No private benefit or non-exempt purposes embedded in purpose statement.
- Member structure and director counts meet state statutory minimums.
- All mandatory state clauses included verbatim when required.
- Any statutory citations confirmed or marked `[VERIFY]`.

## Guidelines

- Do not include shareholder/stock concepts; nonprofit corporations do not issue shares.
- Avoid language implying substantial commercial activity or political campaign intervention.
- Keep purpose language broad but tied to actual activities and exempt categories.
- If state law mandates specific phrasing, use it verbatim and cite the statute; use `[VERIFY]` if uncertain.
- Do not promise tax-exempt status; limit to organizational test compliance.
- Confirm whether the state requires director/officer listing in the Articles before including personal data.
- Treat indemnification and liability limitation as optional and state-dependent.
